"both punished : the agressor is forced to sue for peace to his inferior on dishonourable conditions ; the deserter refuses the satisfaction offered; and this obstinacy cost him his best friend. This works the natural effect of choler, and turns his rage against him by whom he was last affronted, and most sensibly. The greater anger expels the less; but his character is still preserved. In the mean- time, the Grecian army receives loss on loss, and is half destroyed by a pestilence into the bargain."